This paper deals with the complexity of finding a small strong backdoor in constraint satisfaction problems (CSPs), which is a fundamental problem in computer science. The paper uses techniques from parameterized complexity theory to analyze the problem, which is a common approach in the subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper focuses on the tractability of constraint languages, which is a central topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the complexity of the problem in terms of the size of the backdoor and the arity of the constraints, which are concepts that are relevant to computational complexity (cs.CC) and logic (cs.LO). Finally, the paper deals with the structure of constraint languages, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
